  <a href="#1" id="1">
   After Kingston, then New York's capital, was burned in October 1777 by the British, New York Gov. George Clinton received a letter from South Carolina Gov. Abraham Livingston.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The letter included nearly 1,000 New York pounds to help Kingston residents get through their crisis.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   "This money has been received for the charitable purpose of alleviating the distresses of the now-indigent inhabitants of the town of Kingston, who by the ravages of the enemy are reduced to poverty and want," Livingston wrote on March 31, 1778.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Kingston Historian Edwin Ford remembered the letter when Hurricane Hugo ravaged the Carolinas last week.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   "I figured they helped us, we should do something for them," Ford said.
  </a>
